HEADWORD: Meek
<hw>Meek</hw> <pr>(m⟦emac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Meeker</adjf>
<pr>(m⟦emac⟧k"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Meekest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mek</ets>,
<ets>meoc</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>mj⟦umac⟧kr</ets> mild, soft, Sw.
<ets>mjuk</ets>, Dan. <ets>myg</ets>, D. <ets>muik</ets>, Goth.
<ets>muka</ets>m⟦omac⟧dei gentleness.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mild of
temper; not easily provoked or irritated; patient under injuries; not
vain, or haughty, or resentful; forbearing; submissive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now the man Moses was very <qex>meek</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xii.
3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Evincing mildness of temper, or patience;
characterized by mildness or patience; <as>as, a <ex>meek</ex> answer; a
<ex>meek</ex> face.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Her <xex>meek</xex> prayer.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Gentle; mild; soft; yielding; pacific;
unassuming; humble. See <er>Gentle</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

